nce, France":"Chaumont-en-Vexin, Oise, Hauts-de-France, France","Chaumont-en-Vexin, Oise, Picardie, France":"Chaumont-en-Vexin, Oise, Picardie, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bernard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>ber(n)</i> ‘bear’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’. This was the name of three famous medieval churchmen:  St Bernard  of Menthon (  923–1008 ), founder of a hospice on each of the Alpine passes named after him; the monastic reformer  St Bernard  of Clairvaux (  1090–1153 ); and the scholastic philosopher  Bernard  of Chartres. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England. A native Old English form, <i>Beornheard</i>, was superseded by the Norman form."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Bernard de Chaumont-en-Vexin was born in 1180, in Chaumont-en-Vexin, Oise, Hauts-de-France, France, his father, Hugues III De Chaumont en Vexin, was 30 and his mother, Pétronille De Poissy, was 21. He had at least 2 daughters with Aélis de Gisors. He died in 1238, in his hometown, at the age of 58, and was buried in Chaumont-en-Vexin, Oise, Hauts-de-France, France."},"et":{"1180–1238":"1180–1238","1180–1239